   <abstract >We present a comprehensive study of the dimension-6 Standard Model Effective Field Theory (SMEFT) aimed at constraining new physics through a global fit of a broad selection of collider observables. In particular we focus on electroweak and Higgs-boson production cross sections and decay rates, evaluate them in the SMEFT including state-of-the-art Standard Model predictions and up to quadratic terms in the dimension-6 operators, and use our results to test the consistency of the SMEFT approach and to constrain its free parameters (Wilson coefficients) via a global fit of collider data that also include top-quark observables. Through an incremental approach, we test the constraining power of the global fits due to different sets of observables, as well as the impact of theoretical refinements that include in our case the evolution of the Wilson coefficients from the scale of new physics to the electroweak scale and the consideration of dimension-6 quadratic corrections in the perturbative expansion of the SMEFT. Overall, the global analysis presented in this work already provides meaningful constraints on the SMEFT and supports the validity of the SMEFT approach for a broad spectrum of extensions of the Standard Model. It hence sets the framework for future studies that will further benefit from constantly evolving theoretical predictions and the outstanding precision made available by the high-luminosity Large Hadron Collider (HL-LHC).</abstract>
